	<head title="CfPBoK paper entry" />
	<body>
		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/paper18</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Streamlining Control Flow Graph Construction with DCFlow</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarkHills.html">Mark Hills</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_18">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_18</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It introduces DCFlow, a DSL for specifying control-flow rules at the language AST level.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> DCFlow definitions are compiled into generated Rascal code that constructs CFGs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It is delivered as a DSL plus libraries supporting CFG extraction within a workbench setting.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Generated CFGs can be visualized, and the paper discusses visualization as a use of the produced graphs.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
